const e=`### Project Description\r
\r
**Frankie** is a group project exploring the amalgamation of three raw materials—wood, wire, and earth—into a structural pavilion built at a 1:1 scale. The project focuses on material interaction, structural stability, and parametric precision in construction.\r
\r
### Key Features\r
\r
- Integration of wood, wire, and earth in structural design\r
- Exploration of tensile and compressive material properties\r
- CNC-milled precision for joint accuracy\r
- 10,000m of sewing thread used for structural fusion\r
- Modular and adaptable construction\r
\r
### Process\r
\r
The project began with material testing to understand how wood can be manipulated through sewing techniques. By stitching two pieces of bent wood together, a reversible bending effect was achieved, forming a structural system. Wire was then used to connect the wooden frame to a rammed earth base, reinforcing both elements without additional supports.\r
\r
Scaling up to a three-meter-high pavilion introduced challenges requiring CNC-milled joints. A digital 3D model ensured millimeter precision in overlapping holes for sewing, allowing for an efficient and accurate assembly process.\r
\r
### Implementation\r
\r
- Material Experimentation: Understanding the interaction of wood, wire, and earth\r
- Structural Innovation: Using thread-based fusion techniques for tensile and compressive strength\r
- Digital Fabrication: CNC-milled joints for precision assembly\r
- Counterweight System: Bricks integrated to provide additional stability\r
\r
### Design Principles\r
\r
- Material Synergy: Exploring the natural properties of wood, wire, and earth\r
- Parametric Precision: Digital modeling to ensure seamless assembly\r
- Adaptive Construction: A modular approach allowing for iterative refinement\r
`;export{e as default};
